{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"779b93d9-f7d6-4045-a11e-77e6e147f95f","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    public App()\n    {\n        InitializeComponent();\n    }\n\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        var window = new Window(new AppShell());\n\n        window.Created   += (s, e) => Log(\"Created\");\n        window.Activated += (s, e) => Log(\"Activated\");\n        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Log(\"Deactivated\");\n        window.Stopped   += (s, e) => Log(\"Stopped\");\n        window.Resumed   += (s, e) => Log(\"Resumed\");\n        window.Destroying += (s, e) => Log(\"Destroying\");\n\n        // Optional — background/foreground visibility\n        window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Log(\"Backgrounding\");\n\n        return window;\n    }\n\n    static void Log(string evt)\n        => System.Diagnostics.Debug.WriteLine($\"[Window] {evt} at {DateTime.Now:T}\");\n}\n```\n\n**Typical lifecycle order:**\n\n| Transition | Events fired |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| User switches away | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| User returns | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |\n\n> **Tip:** `Backgrounding` only fires on iOS/Mac Catalyst. On Android, `Stopped` serves the same role.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"00d8ba17-1f80-4a85-b801-92d9c05f0414","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":456,"requestId":"9BD5:12ABA3:62AC422:6DDE55B:69EC0E9E"},"id":"37dd3a1f-872c-4d20-8178-6f5169508bf3","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:45:28.604Z","parentId":"89596b2c-e139-4e4b-ba2e-8892d55c71cc"}
